None, 'body': "Hi, 

On branch `xray-gettingstarted` using `2-deploy.sh` fails to create stack properly. My user has admin access.
Below are few things I did to make it work. Please see if we can fix this or if I am doing something wrong. 
Hopefully this is helpful for anyone else facing same issues. I am not sure if these are ideal fixes but I was able to being up the stack.

1. Minor: stack complains its using unsupported platform version. I changed `arn:aws:elasticbeanstalk:::platform/Java 8 running on 64bit Amazon Linux` to `arn:aws:elasticbeanstalk:::platform/Corretto 8 running on 64bit Amazon Linux 2/3.2.5`.
2. stack creation failed due to error `Attribute: EndpointURL was not found for resource: BETA. Rollback requested by user.` Underlying errors that caused this:
2.2. `AWSEBLoadBalancer` failed to create with reason `Issue found with the default subnets: VPC vpc-189b1e73 has no internet gateway (Service: AmazonElasticLoadBalancing; Status Code: 409; Error Code: InvalidConfigurationRequest; Request ID: 7b5d4f96-8148-40d5-ba7f-896dc2c74d5c; Proxy: null)`
Solution: I created InternetGateway and assigned to VPC manually
2.3. Elastic BeanStalk environment stack fails with error `WaitCondition timed out. Received 0 conditions when expecting 1`. My guess is, EC2 instance that gets spun up doesn't make HTTPS call to satisfy wait condition.
*Solution*: Not sure if this is a definite fix, but I spun up a EC2 instance with my key pair within same VPC, Security group and added NAT gateway route to routing table and logged in to instance, and executed that https request.
3. Minor: `template.yml` has email parameter, if it's mandatory for updating that email, `2-deploy.sh` script should probably ask for this variable and pass it on.", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aws-samples/eb-java-scorekeep/issues/16/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aws-samples/eb-java-scorekeep/issues/16/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

On branch `xray-gettingstarted` using `2-deploy.sh` fails to create stack properly. My user has admin access.
Below are few things I did to make it work. Please see if we can fix this or if I am doing something wrong. 
Hopefully this is helpful for anyone else facing same issues. I am not sure if these are ideal fixes but I was able to being up the stack.

1. Minor: stack complains its using unsupported platform version. I changed `arn:aws:elasticbeanstalk:::platform/Java 8 running on 64bit Amazon Linux` to `arn:aws:elasticbeanstalk:::platform/Corretto 8 running on 64bit Amazon Linux 2/3.2.5`.
2. stack creation failed due to error `Attribute: EndpointURL was not found for resource: BETA. Rollback requested by user.` Underlying errors that caused this:
2.2. `AWSEBLoadBalancer` failed to create with reason `Issue found with the default subnets: VPC vpc-189b1e73 has no internet gateway (Service: AmazonElasticLoadBalancing; Status Code: 409; Error Code: InvalidConfigurationRequest; Request ID: 7b5d4f96-8148-40d5-ba7f-896dc2c74d5c; Proxy: null)`
Solution: I created InternetGateway and assigned to VPC manually
2.3. Elastic BeanStalk environment stack fails with error `WaitCondition timed out. Received 0 conditions when expecting 1`. My guess is, EC2 instance that gets spun up doesn't make HTTPS call to satisfy wait condition.
*Solution*: Not sure if this is a definite fix, but I spun up a EC2 instance with my key pair within same VPC, Security group and added NAT gateway route to routing table and logged in to instance, and executed that https request.
3. Minor: `template.yml` has email parameter, if it's mandatory for updating that email, `2-deploy.sh` script should probably ask for this variable and pass it on.", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aws-samples/eb-java-scorekeep/issues/16/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aws-samples/eb-java-scorekeep/issues/16/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}, 'comment': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aws-samples/eb-java-scorekeep/issues/comments/1098614440', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/aws-samples/eb-java-scorekeep/issues/16#issuecomment-1098614440', 'issue_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aws-samples/eb-java-scorekeep/issues/16', 'id': 1098614440, 'node_id': 'IC_kwDOBFG33s5Be4ao', 'user': {'login': 'mwunderl', 'id': 8669825, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjg2Njk4MjU=', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/8669825?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mwunderl', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/mwunderl', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mwunderl/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mwunderl/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mwunderl/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mwunderl/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mwunderl/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mwunderl/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mwunderl/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mwunderl/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mwunderl/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'created_at': '2022-04-14T01:09:49Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-14T01:09:49Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'body': "Hi Gautam, thanks for your feedback

*Description of changes:*
The packaged version of the scorekeep app is outdated. As mentioned in above issues, it is incompatible with EB and the build fails. The code in this branch is slightly up to date and builds fine but lacks the AWS resources needed for the app to work when uploaded to EB manually.
This PR:
- Creates DDB tables and SNS topic as eb extension rather than CFN template to work with manual code upload process.
- Updated the template to use the Corretto 8. platform since Java 8 is now unsupported.

*Description of changes:*
The packaged version of the scorekeep app is outdated. As mentioned in above issues, it is incompatible with EB and the build fails. The code in this branch is slightly up to date and builds fine but lacks the AWS resources needed for the app to work when uploaded to EB manually.
This PR:
- Creates DDB tables and SNS topic as eb extension rather than CFN template to work with manual code upload process.
- Updated the template to use the Corretto 8. platform since Java 8 is now unsupported.

I didn't see a build error on v1.3 in Java 8 but did encounter a different error when using the random name option in the frontend (`com.fasterxml.jackson.core.JsonParseException: Unexpected character` in `scorekeep.UserFactory.randomName`).

Regarding the proxy configuration, Beanstalk does [require this to be in `.platform/nginx` instead of `.ebextensions/nginx`](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticbeanstalk/latest/dg/using-features.migration-al.html) for AL2. Moving it there causes the deployment to fail. However, if it's removed or left in `.ebextensions` the application works. [nginx.conf](https://github.com/aws-samples/eb-java-scorekeep/blob/xray-gettingstarted/.ebextensions/nginx/nginx.conf#L25-L43) serves the `public` directory at root on port 80, and forwards traffic to `/api` to port 5000 where the Spring API is listening. Without it, Beanstalk sends all traffic to port 5000 and Spring serves the contents of `public` at the root path. So I think we can remove the proxy configuration. *Description of changes:*
The packaged version of the scorekeep app is outdated. As mentioned in above issues, it is incompatible with EB and the build fails. The code in this branch is slightly up to date and builds fine but lacks the AWS resources needed for the app to work when uploaded to EB manually.
This PR:
- Creates DDB tables and SNS topic as eb extension rather than CFN template to work with manual code upload process.
- Updated the template to use the Corretto 8. platform since Java 8 is now unsupported.

*Description of changes:*
The packaged version of the scorekeep app is outdated. As mentioned in above issues, it is incompatible with EB and the build fails. The code in this branch is slightly up to date and builds fine but lacks the AWS resources needed for the app to work when uploaded to EB manually.
This PR:
- Creates DDB tables and SNS topic as eb extension rather than CFN template to work with manual code upload process.
- Updated the template to use the Corretto 8. platform since Java 8 is now unsupported.

*Description of changes:*
The packaged version of the scorekeep app is outdated. As mentioned in above issues, it is incompatible with EB and the build fails. The code in this branch is slightly up to date and builds fine but lacks the AWS resources needed for the app to work when uploaded to EB manually.
This PR:
- Creates DDB tables and SNS topic as eb extension rather than CFN template to work with manual code upload process.
- Updated the template to use the Corretto 8. platform since Java 8 is now unsupported.

*Description of changes:*
The packaged version of the scorekeep app is outdated. As mentioned in above issues, it is incompatible with EB and the build fails. The code in this branch is slightly up to date and builds fine but lacks the AWS resources needed for the app to work when uploaded to EB manually.
This PR:
- Creates DDB tables and SNS topic as eb extension rather than CFN template to work with manual code upload process.
- Updated the template to use the Corretto 8. platform since Java 8 is now unsupported.

*Description of changes:*
The packaged version of the scorekeep app is outdated. As mentioned in above issues, it is incompatible with EB and the build fails. The code in this branch is slightly up to date and builds fine but lacks the AWS resources needed for the app to work when uploaded to EB manually.
This PR:
- Creates DDB tables and SNS topic as eb extension rather than CFN template to work with manual code upload process.
- Updated the template to use the Corretto 8. platform since Java 8 is now unsupported.

*Description of changes:*
The packaged version of the scorekeep app is outdated. As mentioned in above issues, it is incompatible with EB and the build fails. The code in this branch is slightly up to date and builds fine but lacks the AWS resources needed for the app to work when uploaded to EB manually.
This PR:
- Creates DDB tables and SNS topic as eb extension rather than CFN template to work with manual code upload process.
- Updated the template to use the Corretto 8. platform since Java 8 is now unsupported.

*Description of changes:*
The packaged version of the scorekeep app is outdated. As mentioned in above issues, it is incompatible with EB and the build fails. The code in this branch is slightly up to date and builds fine but lacks the AWS resources needed for the app to work when uploaded to EB manually.
This PR:
- Creates DDB tables and SNS topic as eb extension rather than CFN template to work with manual code upload process.
- Updated the template to use the Corretto 8. platform since Java 8 is now unsupported.


By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

*Description of changes:*
The packaged version of the scorekeep app is outdated. As mentioned in above issues, it is incompatible with EB and the build fails. The code in this branch is slightly up to date and builds fine but lacks the AWS resources needed for the app to work when uploaded to EB manually.
This PR:
- Creates DDB tables and SNS topic as eb extension rather than CFN template to work with manual code upload process.
- Updated the template to use the Corretto 8. platform since Java 8 is now unsupported.


By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

Release notes

Sourced from tensorflow's releases.

TensorFlow 2.5.3

Release 2.5.3

Note: This is the last release in the 2.5 series.

This releases introduces several vulnerability fixes:

  • Fixes a floating point division by 0 when executing convolution operators (CVE-2022-21725)
  • Fixes a heap OOB read in shape inference for ReverseSequence (CVE-2022-21728)
  • Fixes a heap OOB access in Dequantize (CVE-2022-21726)
  • Fixes an integer overflow in shape inference for Dequantize (CVE-2022-21727)
  • Fixes a heap OOB access in FractionalAvgPoolGrad (CVE-2022-21730)
  • Fixes an overflow and divide by zero in UnravelIndex (CVE-2022-21729)
  • Fixes a type confusion in shape inference for ConcatV2 (CVE-2022-21731)
  • Fixes an OOM in ThreadPoolHandle (CVE-2022-21732)
  • Fixes an OOM due to integer overflow in StringNGrams (CVE-2022-21733)
  • Fixes more issues caused by incomplete validation in boosted trees code (CVE-2021-41208)
  • Fixes an integer overflows in most sparse component-wise ops (CVE-2022-23567)
  • Fixes an integer overflows in AddManySparseToTensorsMap (CVE-2022-23568)
  • Fixes a number of CHECK-failures in MapStage (CVE-2022-21734)
  • Fixes a division by zero in FractionalMaxPool (CVE-2022-21735)
  • Fixes a number of CHECK-fails when building invalid/overflowing tensor shapes (CVE-2022-23569)
  • Fixes an undefined behavior in SparseTensorSliceDataset (CVE-2022-21736)
  • Fixes an assertion failure based denial of service via faulty bin count operations (CVE-2022-21737)
  • Fixes a reference binding to null pointer in QuantizedMaxPool (CVE-2022-21739)
  • Fixes an integer overflow leading to crash in SparseCountSparseOutput (CVE-2022-21738)
  • Fixes a heap overflow in SparseCountSparseOutput (CVE-2022-21740)
  • Fixes an FPE in BiasAndClamp in TFLite (CVE-2022-23557)
  • Fixes an FPE in depthwise convolutions in TFLite (CVE-2022-21741)
  • Fixes an integer overflow in TFLite array creation (CVE-2022-23558)
  • Fixes an integer overflow in TFLite (CVE-2022-23559)
  • Fixes a dangerous OOB write in TFLite (CVE-2022-23561)
  • Fixes a vulnerability leading to read and write outside of bounds in TFLite (CVE-2022-23560)
  • Fixes a set of vulnerabilities caused by using insecure temporary files (CVE-2022-23563)
  • Fixes an integer overflow in Range resulting in undefined behavior and OOM (CVE-2022-23562)
  • Fixes a vulnerability where missing validation causes tf.sparse.split to crash when axis is a tuple (CVE-2021-41206)
  • Fixes a CHECK-fail when decoding resource handles from proto (CVE-2022-23564)
  • Fixes a CHECK-fail with repeated AttrDef (CVE-2022-23565)
  • Fixes a heap OOB write in Grappler (CVE-2022-23566)
  • Fixes a CHECK-fail when decoding invalid tensors from proto (CVE-2022-23571)
  • Fixes an unitialized variable access in AssignOp (CVE-2022-23573)
  • Fixes an integer overflow in OpLevelCostEstimator::CalculateTensorSize (CVE-2022-23575)
  • Fixes an integer overflow in OpLevelCostEstimator::CalculateOutputSize (CVE-2022-23576)
  • Fixes a null dereference in GetInitOp (CVE-2022-23577)
  • Fixes a memory leak when a graph node is invalid (CVE-2022-23578)
  • Fixes an abort caused by allocating a vector that is too large (CVE-2022-23580)
  • Fixes multiple CHECK-failures during Grappler's IsSimplifiableReshape (CVE-2022-23581)
  • Fixes multiple CHECK-failures during Grappler's SafeToRemoveIdentity (CVE-2022-23579)
  • Fixes multiple CHECK-failures in TensorByteSize (CVE-2022-23582)
  • Fixes multiple CHECK-failures in binary ops due to type confusion (CVE-2022-23583)

... (truncated)

None, 'body': "The Media class documentation in the application SDK reference lists the arguments of the `add_label` method in `(x, y, text)` order:

https://github.com/awsdocs/aws-panorama-developer-guide/blob/b712d57cb7fbb3d45bf804b7c6f13f562902c781/resources/applicationsdk-reference.md?plain=1#L204

Instead, the correct argument order when calling this method is `(text, x, y)`, as it is correctly listed in the example of the same doc:

https://github.com/awsdocs/aws-panorama-developer-guide/blob/b712d57cb7fbb3d45bf804b7c6f13f562902c781/resources/applicationsdk-reference.md?plain=1#L270

If you can `add_label` with the wrong order of arguments, no type-checking is done on the python side, and your application will crash a very ugly C++ error like `terminate called after throwing an instance of 'std::logic_error' what(): basic_string::_M_construct null not valid`, without any python call stack provided which makes debugging even harder.", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/awsdocs/aws-panorama-developer-guide/issues/10/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/awsdocs/aws-panorama-developer-guide/issues/10/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}}
